{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:10:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17791"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74975"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60481"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2896"},{"type":"tags","id":"3560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24515"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74975"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic feeling unwell. She reports increased appetite, muscle weakness, itching, restlessness, anxiety, amenorrhoea, and heat intolerance. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Notable findings include exophthalmos, lid lag, and periorbital oedema. A pregnancy test is negative. Thyroid function testing reveals the presence of thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Graves\u0027 disease","Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis","Subacute thyroiditis","Toxic multinodular goitre","Pituitary adenoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with hyperthyroidism, including increased appetite, muscle weakness, and heat intolerance. The presence of exophthalmos, lid lag, and periorbital oedema are classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease\u003C/strong\u003E, an autoimmune disorder that leads to hyperthyroidism. The confirmation of thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI) further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition that typically leads to hypothyroidism, not hyperthyroidism, and is not associated with exophthalmos or TSI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacute thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause transient hyperthyroidism but is usually associated with a painful thyroid gland and does not cause exophthalmos or involve TSI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic multinodular goitre\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hyperthyroidism but is not associated with exophthalmos or TSI. It presents with a palpable nodular thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hyperthyroidism if it secretes thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), but it would not cause exophthalmos or involve TSI. It would also present with other symptoms related to pituitary dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Graves\u0027 disease is an autoimmune disorder characterised by hyperthyroidism, often presenting with symptoms such as increased appetite, muscle weakness, and heat intolerance.","Exophthalmos and periorbital oedema are classic signs associated with Graves\u0027 disease.","Thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins (TSI) are present in Graves\u0027 disease, confirming the diagnosis."],"references":["Ginsberg J. Diagnosis and management of Graves\u0027 disease. CMAJ. 2003 Mar 4;168(5):575-85. PMID: 12615754; PMCID: PMC149254.","Menconi F, Marcocci C, Marin\u00f2 M. Diagnosis and classification of Graves\u0027 disease. Autoimmun Rev. 2014 Apr-May;13(4-5):398-402. doi: 10.1016/j.autrev.2014.01.013. Epub 2014 Jan 12. PMID: 24424182.","Hoang TD, Stocker DJ, Chou EL, Burch HB. 2022 Update on Clinical Management of Graves Disease and Thyroid Eye Disease. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2022 Jun;51(2):287-304. doi: 10.1016/j.ecl.2021.12.004. Epub 2022 May 11. PMID: 35662442; PMCID: PMC9174594."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60481"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17791"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60481"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T13:05:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:13:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10505"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74975"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type